INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b4fb1f38-4373-4631-8d76-0a8105393e1e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Sass + Stylelint + PostCSS — A Lint Pipeline That Actually Understands Your Partials$escape$,
  $escape$Stylelint's default config chokes on Sass-specific syntax like `@use`, `@forward`, and `%placeholders`. The fix: swap the standard parser for `postcss-scss` and extend `stylelint-config-standard-scss` instead of `stylelint-config-standard`.

In your `.stylelintrc.json`, set `"customSyntax": "postcss-scss"` so Stylelint parses interpolations (`#{$var}`), `@each`, and `@mixin` without false positives. Pair this with `stylelint-scss` for Sass-aware rules — `scss/no-duplicate-dollar-variables`, `scss/at-rule-no-unknown`, and `scss/dollar-variable-pattern` are worth enabling from day one.

For Prettier, set `"parser": "scss"` in your config or rely on file-extension detection. Prettier 3+ handles nested rules and Sass control flow well, but it won't touch `@extend` chains — keep those short manually.

The PostCSS pipeline slot matters: run `postcss-import` first to resolve `@use` aliases, then Autoprefixer, then cssnano in production. Don't run cssnano during lint — it mutates selectors in ways that break Stylelint's source-map tracking. Wire everything together in `postcss.config.mjs` with environment guards.$escape$,
  $escape$// .stylelintrc.json
{
  "customSyntax": "postcss-scss",
  "extends": ["stylelint-config-standard-scss"],
  "plugins": ["stylelint-scss"],
  "rules": {
    "scss/no-duplicate-dollar-variables": true,
    "scss/at-rule-no-unknown": true,
    "scss/dollar-variable-pattern": "^[a-z][a-z0-9-]*$"
  }
}

// postcss.config.mjs
export default {
  plugins: [
    "postcss-import",
    "autoprefixer",
    ...(process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? ["cssnano"] : [])
  ]
};$escape$,
